## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Also removed |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown by the runtime |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can interrupt `finally` blocks, leave locks held, and corrupt shared data.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must observe the CancellationToken for reliable cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules on the thread pool (no manual Thread needed)
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            // Wait will throw OperationCanceledException if the token fires
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // AggregateException from Task.Run is unwrapped by GetAwaiter().GetResult(),
        // so the original exception propagates naturally — no manual wrapping needed.
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred in modern code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — work ignores cancellation
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work observes the token
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),   // pass token through
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// Or async:
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowDatabaseCallAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Critical Pitfall: Cooperative Cancellation

Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation tokens are **cooperative** — the work must check them. If you're wrapping code you can't modify:

```csharp
// For uncooperative work that ignores the token:
// The caller stops waiting, but the work continues on a background thread.
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();

    // ⚠️ The work is NOT stopped — it keeps running.
    // This is intentional: forceful termination corrupts state.
    throw new TimeoutException(
        $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

This is an **inherent trade-off** — there is no safe way to forcibly kill work in .NET 8. If you truly need process-level isolation for untrusted/uncooperative code, run it in a **separate process** and kill that process on timeout.
